Next, the Short Time Fourier Transform¶

The STFT represents a signal in the time-frequency domain by computing discrete Fourier transforms (DFT) over short overlapping windows.

In [83]:
# Get the audio and sample rate
test, test_sr = librosa.load(test_clip_fp, sr = 8000, mono=True)
In [47]:
print(test)

[-9.1552734e-05 -9.1552734e-05 -6.1035156e-05 ...  3.0517578e-05
  3.3569336e-04  2.7465820e-04]
In [48]:
print(len(test))

480000
In [49]:
print(test_sr)

8000

It looks like everything is what we expected. The number of samples (length of the array) is the duration in seconds (60) * sample_rate (8000)

test is an array of time series data

Next, we set set the frame size (size of each window we are looking at) and hop size (increment we move the frame size over for analysis). Note that we are analyzing overlapping frames.

In [50]:
FRAME_SIZE = 2048
HOP_SIZE = 512
In [51]:
s_test = librosa.stft(test, n_fft = FRAME_SIZE, hop_length = HOP_SIZE)
In [52]:
s_test.shape
Out[52]:

Note that the second dimension of shape is the number of "hops" we made while calculating the STFT as verified with the following calculation

In [66]:
def plot_spectromgram(Y, sr, hop_length, y_axis = 'linear'):
    plt.figure(figsize=(25, 10))
    librosa.display.specshow(Y,
                            sr = test_sr,
                            x_axis = 'time',
                            y_axis = y_axis)
    plt.colorbar(format="%+2.f")
    plt.savefig('test_spectrogram.png')

In [114]:
# First let's calculate the MFCCs from the Melspectrogram
S = librosa.feature.melspectrogram(y=test, sr=test_sr, n_mels=128, fmax=8000)
mfccs1 = librosa.feature.mfcc(S=librosa.power_to_db(S), n_mfcc=13)
print(mfccs1)

Depending on the transformations you do ahead of time, you get completely different answers for the MFCCs

In [117]:
# Shapes should be the same
print(mfccs1.shape)
print(mfccs2.shape)

(13, 938)
(13, 938)

The first dimension is the number of coeeficients, which we set to 13. We have seen it set to 13, 20, and 40 in the different readings we have done. The 938 is still based on the hop size

# From Librosa tutorial: https://librosa.org/doc/main/generated/librosa.feature.mfcc.html
fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=2, figsize=(12,8), sharex=True)
img = librosa.display.specshow(librosa.power_to_db(S, ref=np.max), x_axis='time', y_axis='mel', fmax=8000, ax=ax[0])
fig.colorbar(img, ax=[ax[0]])
ax[0].set(title='Mel spectrogram')
ax[0].label_outer()
img = librosa.display.specshow(mfccs1, x_axis='time', ax=ax[1])
fig.colorbar(img, ax=[ax[1]])
ax[1].set(title='MFCC')
